A special fund was established for victims of Agent Orange, with donations primarily from domestic sources.
Managed by the Red Cross, it aims to aid those affected by the toxic chemical.
Recent studies show decreasing dioxin levels from the Vietnam War era.
Despite ongoing demining efforts, buried dioxin remains a concern.
The fund's creation highlights the growing impact on a third generation of victims.
Efforts to address the issue include a census to identify and support those affected, particularly in central and northern Vietnam.
The legacy of Agent Orange continues to affect communities, necessitating ongoing research and support.
